--Word--|dayman |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|A man who is hired or paid by the day; a day labourer; specifically a colliery worker who is paid for the amount of time worked, rather than by the weight of coal produced. Compare daysman. Now chiefly historical.|A man (especially a shift worker) who works during the day as opposed to at night.|Nautical. A member of a ship's crew (as a carpenter, cook, sailmaker, etc.) who works only during the day, not being required to assist in keeping watch.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Damocles |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|A legendary courtier who extravagantly praised the happiness of Dionysius I, ruler of Syracuse. To show him how precarious this happiness was, Dionysius seated him at a banquet with a sword hung by a single hair over his head.|--Examples--|
--Word--|Damon |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|A legendary Syracusan of the 4th century BC whose friend Pythias (also called Phintias) was sentenced to death by Dionysius I. Damon stood bail for Pythias, who returned just in time to save him, and was himself reprieved.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Danton, Georges |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(1759–94), French revolutionary; full name Georges Jacques Danton. A noted orator, he won great popularity in the early days of the French Revolution. He was initially an ally of Robespierre but later revolted against the severity of the Revolutionary Tribunal and was executed on Robespierre's orders.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Dardanelles |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|A narrow strait between Europe and Asiatic Turkey (called the Hellespont in classical times), linking the Sea of Marmara with the Aegean Sea. --Word--|Darwinize |--Type--|verb|--Meanings--|To speculate about the evolution of life, after the manner of Erasmus Darwin; to write in the poetic style of Erasmus Darwin. Now historical.|To speculate or theorize about evolution in the light of Charles Darwin's theory.|To subject to evolution or selective competition in a manner considered to be Darwinian; to modify or eliminate by means of natural or artificial selection. Also without object: to evolve or be transformed in this way.|To cause (a person) to accept Darwinism; to subject to the influence of Darwinism; to incorporate Charles Darwin's ideas or principles into (a theory or discipline); to consider or treat (a subject) in the light of Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection.|--Examples--|

--Word--|dash |--Type--|verb, exclamation, noun|--Meanings--|Run or travel somewhere in a great hurry.|Strike or fling (something) somewhere with great force, especially so as to have a destructive effect; hurl.|Strike forcefully against something.|Destroy or frustrate (hopes or expectations)|Cause (someone) to lose confidence; dispirit.|Used to express mild annoyance.|An act of running somewhere suddenly and hastily.|A journey or period of time characterized by urgency or eager haste.|A short, fast race run in one heat; a sprint.|A small quantity of a liquid added to something else.|A small amount of a quality that adds piquancy or distinctiveness to something else.|A horizontal stroke in writing or printing to mark a pause or break in sense or to represent omitted letters or words.|The longer signal of the two used in Morse code.|A short vertical mark placed above or beneath a note to indicate that it is to be performed in a very staccato manner.|Impetuous or flamboyant vigour and confidence; panache.|dash something off|Write something hurriedly and without much premeditation.|--Examples--|I dashed into the garden|I must dash, I'm late|the ship was dashed upon the rocks|a gust of rain dashed against the bricks|the budget dashed hopes of an increase in funding|I won't tell Stuart—I think he'd be dashed|dash it all, I am in charge|she made a dash for the door|a 20-mile dash to the airport|the 100 m dash|whisky with a dash of soda|a casual atmosphere with a dash of sophistication|he has youthful energy, dash, and charisma|an indicator on the dash tells you what gear you are in|I dashed off a quick letter|

--Word--|David |--Type--|proper noun, proper noun|--Meanings--|(died c.962 BC), king of Judah and Israel c.1000–c.962 BC. In the biblical account he was the youngest son of Jesse and killed the Philistine Goliath; on Saul's death, he became king, making Jerusalem his capital. He is traditionally regarded as the author of the Psalms, though this has been disputed.|The name of two kings of Scotland.|David I (c.1084–1153), sixth son of Malcolm III, reigned 1124–53. In 1136 he invaded England in support of his niece Matilda's claim to the throne, but was defeated at the Battle of the Standard in 1138.|David II (1324–71), son of Robert the Bruce, reigned 1329–71. His reign witnessed a renewal of fighting with England, with Edward III supporting the pretender Edward de Baliol. His death without issue left the throne to the Stuarts.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Black Death |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|The great epidemic of a disease thought to be bubonic plague, which killed a large proportion of the population of Europe in the mid 14th century. It originated in central Asia and China and spread rapidly through Europe, carried by the fleas of black rats, reaching England in 1348 and killing between one third and one half of the population in a matter of months.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Debussy, Claude |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(1862–1918), French composer and critic; full name Achille Claude Debussy. Debussy carried the ideas of impressionist art and symbolist poetry into music, using melodies based on the whole-tone scale and delicate harmonies exploiting overtones. Notable works: Prélude à l'après-midi d'un faune (1894).|--Examples--|

--Word--|decillion |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Originally: the cardinal number equal to the tenth power of a million, represented by 1 followed by sixty zeros (1060) (now chiefly British). Later also (originally US): the cardinal number equal to the eleventh power of a thousand, or 1 followed by thirty-three zeros (1033). Also hyperbolically: an unspecified but very large number or amount.|--Examples--|

--Word--|decline |--Type--|verb, noun|--Meanings--|(typically of something regarded as good) become smaller, fewer, or less; decrease.|Diminish in strength or quality; deteriorate.|Politely refuse (an invitation or offer)|(especially of the sun) move downwards.|Bend down; droop.|(in the grammar of Latin, Greek, and certain other languages) state the forms of (a noun, pronoun, or adjective) corresponding to case, number, and gender.|A gradual and continuous loss of strength, numbers, quality, or value.|The sun's gradual setting.|A disease in which the bodily strength gradually fails, especially tuberculosis.|--Examples--|the birth rate continued to decline|her health began to decline|Caroline declined the coffee|the company declined to comment|the sun began to creep round to the west and to decline|the wearisome creatures of the world declining to their rest|a serious decline in bird numbers|a civilization in decline|this Evening from the Sun's decline arriv'd|he died at his brother's of a deep decline|

--Word--|Defoe, Daniel |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(1660–1731), English novelist and journalist. His best-known novel, Robinson Crusoe (1719), is loosely based on the true story of the shipwrecked sailor Alexander Selkirk; it has a claim to being the first English novel. Other notable works: Moll Flanders (novel, 1722) and A Journal of the Plague Year (historical fiction, 1722).|--Examples--|

--Word--|Deirdre |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|A tragic heroine of whom it was prophesied that her beauty would bring banishment and death to heroes. King Conchobar of Ulster wanted to marry her, but she fell in love with Naoise, son of Usnach, who with his brothers carried her off to Scotland. --Word--|deny |--Type--|verb|--Meanings--|State that one refuses to admit the truth or existence of.|Refuse to admit the truth of (a concept or proposition that is supported by the majority of scientific or historical evidence)|Refuse to give (something requested or desired) to (someone)|Refuse to let oneself have something that one desires.|Refuse access to (someone)|--Examples--|both firms deny any responsibility for the tragedy|an anti-environmentalist campaign group that denies climate change|the inquiry was denied access to intelligence sources|there was no way that I was going to deny myself ice cream|the servants are ordered to deny him|
--Word--|denier |--Type--|noun, noun|--Meanings--|A person who denies something, especially someone who refuses to admit the truth of a concept or proposition that is supported by the majority of scientific or historical evidence.|A unit of weight by which the fineness of silk, rayon, or nylon yarn is measured, equal to the weight in grams of 9,000 metres of the yarn and often used to describe the thickness of hosiery.|A former French coin, equal to one twelfth of a sou, which was withdrawn in the 19th century.|--Examples--|a prominent denier of global warming|a climate change denier|15-denier stockings|

--Word--|Denis, St. |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(died c.250), French bishop; born in Italy; patron saint of France; Roman name Dionysius. According to tradition, he was one of a group of seven missionaries sent from Rome to convert Gaul; he became bishop of Paris and was martyred in the reign of the emperor Valerian. Feast day, October 9.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Potter, Dennis |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(1935–94), English television playwright; full name Dennis Christopher George Potter. His work used popular songs to contrast the humdrum or painful realities of everyday life with the imagination's capacity for hope and self-delusion. Notable works: Brimstone and Treacle (play, 1976) and the series Pennies from Heaven (1978) and The Singing Detective (1986).|--Examples--|

--Word--|deposit |--Type--|noun, verb|--Meanings--|A sum of money paid into a bank or building society account.|A sum payable as a first instalment on the purchase of something or as a pledge for a contract, the balance being payable later.|A returnable sum payable on the hire or rental of something, to cover possible loss or damage.|(in the UK) a sum of money lodged by an election candidate and forfeited if they fail to receive a certain proportion of the votes.|A layer or mass of accumulated matter.|A natural underground layer of rock, coal, or other material.|The action of placing something in a specified place.|Put or set down (something or someone) in a specific place.|(of water, the wind, or other natural agency) lay down (matter) gradually as a layer or covering.|Lay (an egg)|Place (something) somewhere for safekeeping.|Pay (a sum of money) into a bank or building society account.|Pay (a sum) as a first instalment or as a pledge for a contract.|--Examples--|cash funds which are an alternative to bank or building society deposits|we've saved enough for a deposit on a house|a refundable €100 deposit is payable on arrival at the villa|he lost his deposit but was credited with contributing to the Conservatives' defeat|the deposits of salt on the paintwork|a great quantity of pottery was found in this deposit|areas of mineral deposits|the deposit of a thesis in a library gives no guarantee of copyright protection|I'd like to make a deposit|he deposited a pile of school books on the kitchen table|beds where salt is deposited by the tide|the female deposits a line of eggs|a vault in which guests may deposit valuable property|the money had been deposited in a Swiss bank account|I had to deposit 10% of the price of the house|
--Word--|depositary |--Type--|noun, adjective|--Meanings--|A person to whom something is lodged in trust.|(of a share or receipt) representing a share in a foreign company. The depositary share or receipt is traded on the stock exchange of the investor's country rather than the actual share, which is deposited in a foreign bank.|--Examples--|in the seventeenth century, goldsmiths acted as depositaries for the gold of the rich|

--Word--|depression |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Feelings of severe despondency and dejection.|A mental condition characterized by feelings of severe despondency and dejection, typically also with feelings of inadequacy and guilt, often accompanied by lack of energy and disturbance of appetite and sleep.|A long and severe recession in an economy or market.|The financial and industrial slump of 1929 and subsequent years.|The action of lowering something or pressing something down.|A sunken place or hollow on a surface.|A region of lower atmospheric pressure, especially a cyclonic weather system.|The angular distance of an object below the horizon or a horizontal plane.|--Examples--|self-doubt creeps in and that swiftly turns to depression|she was referred by a psychiatrist treating her for depression|the depression in the housing market|depression of the plunger delivers two units of insulin|the original shallow depressions were slowly converted to creeks|hurricanes start off as loose regions of bad weather known as tropical depressions|

--Word--|dereliction |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|The state of having been abandoned and become dilapidated.|The shameful failure to fulfil one's obligations.|--Examples--|a 15th-century farmhouse has been saved from dereliction|the prosecution team were guilty of dereliction of duty for failing to disclose evidence|a gross dereliction of duty by the Secretary of State|
--Word--|dereliction |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|The state of having been abandoned and become dilapidated.|The shameful failure to fulfil one's obligations.|--Examples--|a 15th-century farmhouse has been saved from dereliction|the prosecution team were guilty of dereliction of duty for failing to disclose evidence|a gross dereliction of duty by the Secretary of State|
--Word--|derelict |--Type--|adjective, noun|--Meanings--|In a very poor condition as a result of disuse and neglect.|Shamefully negligent of one's duties or obligations.|A person without a home, job, or property.|A ship or other piece of property abandoned by the owner and in poor condition.|--Examples--|a derelict Georgian mansion|the barge lay derelict for years|he was derelict in his duty to his country|derelicts who could fit all their possessions in a paper bag|she had been a derelict recommissioned for this journey|

--Word--|derivative |--Type--|adjective, noun|--Meanings--|Imitative of the work of another artist, writer, etc., and usually disapproved of for that reason.|Originating from, based on, or influenced by.|(of a product) having a value deriving from an underlying variable asset.|Something which is based on another source.|A word derived from another or from a root in the same or another language.|A substance that is derived chemically from a specified compound.|An arrangement or product (such as a future, option, or warrant) whose value derives from and is dependent on the value of an underlying asset, such as a commodity, currency, or security.|An expression representing the rate of change of a function with respect to an independent variable.|--Examples--|an artist who is not in the slightest bit derivative|Darwin's work is derivative of the moral philosophers|equity-based derivative products|the aircraft is a derivative of the Falcon 20G|fly-tip is a derivative of the phrase on the fly|crack is a highly addictive cocaine derivative|the derivatives market|

--Word--|Erasmus, Desiderius |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(c.1469–1536), Dutch humanist and scholar; Dutch name Gerhard Gerhards. He was the foremost Renaissance scholar of northern Europe, paving the way for the Reformation with his satires on the Church, including the Colloquia Familiaria (1518). However, he opposed the violence of the Reformation and condemned Luther in De Libero Arbitrio (1523).|--Examples--|

--Word--|determinism |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|The doctrine that all events, including human action, are ultimately determined by causes regarded as external to the will. Some philosophers have taken determinism to imply that individual human beings have no free will and cannot be held morally responsible for their actions.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Clinton, DeWitt |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(1769–1828), US politician. Among his political positions, he was a member of the New York legislature 1798–1802, 1806–11, a US senator 1802–03, and mayor of New York City 1803–07, 1808–10, 1811–15. As governor of New York 1817–23, 1825–28, he was a champion of the Erie Canal.|--Examples--|

--Word--|dialyser |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Chemistry and Biology. An apparatus containing a semipermeable membrane for the separation of dissolved and suspended substances in a liquid by means of dialysis.|Medicine. An apparatus or machine used to perform therapeutic dialysis; specifically = haemodialyser. --Word--|dialyser |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Chemistry and Biology. An apparatus containing a semipermeable membrane for the separation of dissolved and suspended substances in a liquid by means of dialysis.|Medicine. An apparatus or machine used to perform therapeutic dialysis; specifically = haemodialyser. Also: a detachable unit or cartridge containing membranes or filters for use in a dialysis machine.|--Examples--|

--Word--|dialyser |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Chemistry and Biology. An apparatus containing a semipermeable membrane for the separation of dissolved and suspended substances in a liquid by means of dialysis.|Medicine. An apparatus or machine used to perform therapeutic dialysis; specifically = haemodialyser. Also: a detachable unit or cartridge containing membranes or filters for use in a dialysis machine.|--Examples--|

pressure.|A disc with numbered finger holes on a telephone, rotated a particular distance for each digit of the number being called.|A plate or disc turned to select a setting on a radio, cooker, or other piece of equipment.|A person's face.|Call (a telephone number) by turning a dial or using a keypad.|dial something down|Adjust the control on an electrical device so as to reduce the level of sound, light, heat, etc. produced.|Lessen the amount, intensity, or degree of a quality, factor, etc.|dial in (or into)|Access a computer system or service remotely via a telephone line.|dial something in (or into)|Indicate or regulate by means of a dial.|Include or add.|be (or get) dialled in|Be or become so focused that one is able to perform to the best of one's abilities.|dial up (or dial something up)|Access a computer system or service remotely via a telephone line.|dial something up|Adjust the control on an electrical device so as to increase the level of sound, light, heat, etc. produced.|Increase the amount, intensity, or degree of a quality, factor, etc.|--Examples--|he must be one of the new batch—I haven't seen his dial before|she dialled 999|it took only a moment to dial in the numbers|company employees dial out from their office|after 15 minutes of frustration, someone on the stand took the hint and dialled down the music|he's dialled down the rage that seems to permeate his other novels|having read this review I think I will dial down my expectations a little|there's no need to dial in to see if you have mail|remote workers or travelling employees can dial into the data network|you're expected to dial in volume and tone settings|the car has a lot of understeer dialled into the suspension|I didn't really get dialled in until the final qualifying session|dialling up each time we want to use the Internet will become a thing of the past|people do not have to pay for phone line calls every time they dial up to the internet|plans to enable customers to dial up videos from their living room|even with everything dialled up to full, the audio output level was only moderate at best|the Raiders really dialled up the pressure in the second half|

--Word--|dictionary |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|A book or electronic resource that lists the words of a language (typically in alphabetical order) and gives their meaning, or gives the equivalent words in a different language, often also providing information about pronunciation, origin, and usage.|A reference book on a particular subject, the items of which are typically arranged in alphabetical order.|A set of words or other text strings made for use in applications such as spellcheckers.|--Examples--|I'll look up 'love' in the dictionary|the website gives access to an online dictionary|the dictionary definition of smile|a dictionary of quotations|the worm attempts to crack account passwords using a built-in dictionary|

--Word--|Dictyoxylon |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Originally: †any of various Carboniferous seed ferns of the former genus Dictyoxylon, occurring in the European coal measures as fossil stems having longitudinally-oriented bands of fibres in the outer cortex, often forming an interconnecting network of strands (obsolete). In later use: (attributive) designating this type of cortical structure.|--Examples--|

A leading figure of the Enlightenment in France, he was principal editor of the Encyclopédie (1751–76), through which he disseminated and popularized philosophy and scientific knowledge. Other notable works: Le Rêve de D'Alembert (1782) and Le Neveu de Rameau (1805).|--Examples--|

--Word--|direct |--Type--|adjective, adverb, verb|--Meanings--|Extending or moving from one place to another without changing direction or stopping.|(of apparent planetary motion) proceeding from west to east in accord with actual motion.|Without intervening factors or intermediaries.|(of light or heat) proceeding from a source without being reflected or blocked.|(of genealogy) proceeding in continuous succession from parent to child.|(of a quotation) taken from someone's words without being changed.|(of taxation) levied on income or profits rather than on goods or services.|Complete (used for emphasis)|(of a person or their behaviour) going straight to the point; frank.|(of evidence or proof) bearing immediately and unambiguously upon the facts at issue.|Perpendicular to a surface; not oblique.|With no one or nothing in between.|By a straight route or without breaking a journey.|Control the operations of; manage or govern.|Supervise and control (a film, play, or other production, or the actors in it)|Train and conduct (a group of musicians).|Aim (something) in a particular direction or at a particular person.|Tell or show (someone) how to get somewhere.|Address or give instructions for the delivery of (a letter or parcel)|Focus (one's thoughts) on or address (one's efforts) towards something.|Address a comment to or aim a criticism at.|Target a product or advertisement specifically at (someone)|Guide or advise in a course or decision.|Give (someone) an official order or authoritative instruction.|--Examples--|there was no direct flight that day|the complications are a direct result of bacteria spreading|I had no direct contact with Mr Clark|ferns like a bright position out of direct sunlight|a direct descendant of Edward III|attitudes which were in direct contrast to the confrontational perspectives of the past|he is very direct and honest|there is no direct evidence that officials accepted bribes|a direct butt joint between surfaces of steel|they seem reluctant to deal with me direct|Austrian Airlines are flying direct to Innsbruck again|an economic elite directed the nation's affairs|the film is directed by Sir Richard Attenborough|heating ducts to direct warm air to rear-seat passengers|his smile was directed at Lois|can you direct me to the railway station, please?|put them all in one packet, and direct them to me|his criticism was directed at the wastage of ammunition|I suggest that he direct his remarks to the council|the book is directed at the younger reader|the conscience of the credulous prince was directed by saints and bishops|the judge directed him to perform community service|he directed that no picture from his collection could be sold|

manage or govern.|Supervise and control (a film, play, or other production, or the actors in it)|Train and conduct (a group of musicians).|Aim (something) in a particular direction or at a particular person.|Tell or show (someone) how to get somewhere.|Address or give instructions for the delivery of (a letter or parcel)|Focus (one's thoughts) on or address (one's efforts) towards something.|Address a comment to or aim a criticism at.|Target a product or advertisement specifically at (someone)|Guide or advise in a course or decision.|Give (someone) an official order or authoritative instruction.|--Examples--|there was no direct flight that day|the complications are a direct result of bacteria spreading|I had no direct contact with Mr Clark|ferns like a bright position out of direct sunlight|a direct descendant of Edward III|attitudes which were in direct contrast to the confrontational perspectives of the past|he is very direct and honest|there is no direct evidence that officials accepted bribes|a direct butt joint between surfaces of steel|they seem reluctant to deal with me direct|Austrian Airlines are flying direct to Innsbruck again|an economic elite directed the nation's affairs|the film is directed by Sir Richard Attenborough|heating ducts to direct warm air to rear-seat passengers|his smile was directed at Lois|can you direct me to the railway station, please?|put them all in one packet, and direct them to me|his criticism was directed at the wastage of ammunition|I suggest that he direct his remarks to the council|the book is directed at the younger reader|the conscience of the credulous prince was directed by saints and bishops|the judge directed him to perform community service|he directed that no picture from his collection could be sold|

The data may be stored either magnetically (in a magnetic disk) or optically (in an optical disk such as a CD-ROM).|A CD or record.|One of the suits in some tarot packs, corresponding to coins in others.|An object or part resembling a disc in shape or appearance.|A layer of cartilage separating adjacent vertebrae in the spine.|The central part of the flower of a daisy or other composite plant, consisting of a close-packed cluster of tubular florets.|--Examples--|coins were made by striking a blank disc of metal|a man's body with an identity disc around the neck|the smudged yellow disc of the moon|he suffered a prolapsed disc|

because of completion or breach.|The action of discharging someone from a hospital or from the armed forces or police.|An act of releasing someone from the custody or restraint of the law.|The action of discharging a liquid, gas, or other substance.|A substance that has been discharged.|The release of electricity from a charged object.|A flow of electricity through air or other gas, especially payment of a debt.|The relief of a bankrupt from residual liability.|The cancellation of an order of a court.|--Examples--|Mark was taken away in an ambulance but later discharged|his memory was toxic materials into rivers|the overflow should discharge in an obvious place|the swelling will eventually break down and discharge pus|the eyes and nose began to discharge|the electrostatic field that builds up on a monitor screen can be discharged|batteries have a tendency to discharge slowly|when you shoot you can discharge as many barrels as you wish|there was a dull thud as the gun duties|the executor must discharge the funeral expenses|the insurer is discharged from liability from the day of breach|first-time bankrupts are discharged automatically after three years|the court may discharge a care order on the application of the child|an existing mortgage to be discharged on completion|referrals can be discussed before discharge from hospital|he failed a drug test and was given a dishonourable discharge|she was given an absolute discharge after admitting breaking a smoking ban|those germs might lead to vaginal discharge|industrial discharge has turned the river into an open sewer|a greeny-yellow nasal discharge|slow discharge of a condenser is fundamental to oscillatory circuits|a sizzling discharge between sky and turret|a police permit for discharge of an air gun|sounds like discharges of artillery|freight for discharge|directors must use skill in the discharge of their duties|money paid in discharge of a claim|machinery to rehabilitate the bankrupt --Word--|discipline |--Type--|noun, verb|--Meanings--|The practice of training people to obey rules or a code of behaviour, using punishment to correct disobedience.|The controlled behaviour resulting from such training.|Activity that provides mental or physical training.|A system of rules of conduct.|A branch of knowledge, typically one studied in higher education.|Train (someone) to obey rules or a code of behaviour, using punishment to correct disobedience.|Punish or rebuke formally for an offence.|Train oneself to do something in a controlled and habitual way.|--Examples--|a lack of proper parental and school discipline|he was able to maintain discipline among his men|the tariqa offered spiritual discipline|Kung fu is a discipline open to old and young|he doesn't have to submit to normal disciplines|sociology is a fairly new discipline|many parents have been afraid to discipline their children|a member of staff was to be disciplined by management|every month discipline yourself to go through the file|

Constituting or exhibiting a disconformity; (of a stratum) related to or lying on an underlying stratum that has the same orientation but has undergone erosion, so that the chronological sequence of strata is interrupted.|--Examples--|
--Word--|disconformable |--Type--|adjective|--Meanings--|Geology. Constituting or exhibiting a disconformity; (of a stratum) related to or lying on an underlying stratum that has the same orientation but has undergone erosion, so that the chronological sequence of strata is interrupted.|--Examples--|
--Word--|disconformity |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Lack of conformity.|A break in a sedimentary sequence which does not involve a difference of inclination between the strata on each side of the break.|--Examples--|
--Word--|disconformity |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|Lack of conformity.|A break in a sedimentary sequence which does not involve a difference of inclination between the strata on each side of the break.|--Examples--|

--Word--|disconnect |--Type--|verb, noun|--Meanings--|Break the connection of or between.|Put (an electrical device) out of action by detaching it from a power supply.|Interrupt or terminate (a telephone conversation) by breaking the connection.|Terminate the connection of (a household) to water, electricity, gas, or telephone, typically because of non-payment of bills.|An instance of disconnecting or being disconnected.|A discrepancy or lack of connection.|--Examples--|if the axle unit is partially disconnected from the body, the car should not be driven|he disconnected the main power cables from the batteries|I phoned them in Edinburgh but we got disconnected|if customers agree a payment plan, they will not be disconnected|a disconnect message|there can be a disconnect between boardrooms and IT departments when it comes to technology|

--Word--|dispersion |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|The action or process of distributing things or people over a wide area.|The state of being dispersed.|The pattern of distribution of individuals within a habitat.|A mixture of one substance dispersed in another medium.|The separation of white light into colours or of any radiation according to wavelength.|The extent to which values of a variable differ from a fixed value such as the mean.|--Examples--|some seeds rely on birds for dispersion|the study looks at the dispersion of earnings with OECD member countries|the virus is transmitted in the dispersion of droplets which results from sneezing or coughing|

--Word--|displacement |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|The action of moving something from its place or position.|The removal of someone or something by someone or something else which takes their place.|The enforced departure of people from their homes, typically because of war, persecution, or natural disaster.|The amount by which a thing is moved from a position.|The occupation by a submerged body or part of a body of a volume which would otherwise be occupied by a fluid.|The volume or weight of fluid that would fill the volume displaced by a floating ship, used as a measure of the ship's size.|The volume swept by a reciprocating system, as in a pump or engine.|The unconscious transfer of an intense emotion from one object to another.|The component of an electric field due to free separated charges, regardless of any polarizing effects.|The vector representing such a component.|The flux density of such an electric field.|--Examples--|vertical displacement of the shoreline|a displacement of the vertebra at the bottom of the spine|males may be able to resist displacement by other males|the displacement of farmers by guerrilla activity|a displacement of 6.8 metres along the San Andreas fault|the submarine has a surface displacement of 2,185 tons|a fixed displacement gear|this phobia was linked with the displacement of fear of his father|

--Word--|Disraeli, Benjamin |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|1st Earl of Beaconsfield (1804–81), British Conservative statesman; prime minister 1868 and 1874–80. He was largely responsible for the introduction of the second Reform Act (1867). He also ensured that Britain bought a controlling interest in the Suez Canal (1875) and made Queen Victoria Empress of India.|--Examples--|

--Word--|dissociative |--Type--|adjective|--Meanings--|Causing disconnection or separation.|Denoting or relating to a disorder in which normally related mental processes are separated.|Causing a molecule to split into separate smaller atoms, ions, or molecules, especially in a way that is reversible.|--Examples--|the dissociative force of scepticism has been constantly at work in all of Europe's great ages|it is imperative for future research to determine whether dissociative disorders are exclusively related to trauma|the dynamics of dissociative electron transfer|

--Word--|dissociate |--Type--|verb|--Meanings--|(especially in abstract contexts) disconnect or separate.|Declare that one is not connected with or a supporter of (someone or something)|Split off (a component of mental activity) to act as an independent part of mental life.|(with reference to a molecule) split into separate smaller atoms, ions, or molecules, especially reversibly.|--Examples--|the word spiritual has become for many dissociated from religion|he took pains to dissociate himself from the religious radicals|these compounds are dissociated by solar radiation to yield atoms of chlorine|

--Word--|dissociation |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|The action of disconnecting or separating or the state of being disconnected.|The splitting of a molecule into smaller molecules, atoms, or ions, especially by a reversible process.|Separation of normally related mental processes, resulting in one group functioning independently from the rest, leading in extreme cases to disorders such as multiple personality.|--Examples--|we in the West honour a long-standing dissociation between church and state|the dissociations that one can observe in neuropsychological patients|

--Word--|distributive |--Type--|adjective, noun|--Meanings--|Concerned with the supply of goods to retailers.|Concerned with the way in which things are shared between people.|(of a determiner or pronoun) referring to each individual of a class, not to the class collectively, e.g. each, either.|(of an operation) fulfilling the condition that, when it is performed on two or more quantities already combined by another operation, the result is the same as when it is performed on each quantity individually and the products then combined.|A distributive word.|--Examples--|transport and distributive industries|the distributive effects of public expenditure|

principal taxonomic category that ranks above class and below kingdom, equivalent to the phylum in zoology.|Any subsidiary category between major levels of classification.|A partition.|--Examples--|the division of the land into small fields|a gene that helps regulate cell division|the division of his estates between the two branches of his family|the new clause was agreed without a division|the plant can also be easily increased by division in autumn|a growing sense of division between north and south|deep cultural divisions|no multiplication or division is run.|Make a call increasing the value of the penalty points to be scored on an opponent's bid if it wins the auction and is not fulfilled.|Fold or bend (paper, cloth, or other material) over on itself.|Clench (a fist)|Pot (a ball) by making it rebound off a cushion.|Sail round (a headland)|Be used in or play another, different role.|(of an actor) play (two parts) in the same piece.|Play two or more musical instruments.|Add the same note in a higher or lower octave to (a note).|--Examples--|double doors|she sipped a double brandy|a double bed|the double life of a freelance secret agent|otter is spelled with a double t|large double blooms|the jail now houses almost double the number of prisoners it was designed for|I'll pay double what I paid last time|you have to be careful, and this counts double for older people|join the two sleeping bags together to make a double|Two whiskies, and make it doubles please|you must finish the game on a double|you could pass yourself off as his double|she had seen her husband's double|the semi-finals of the doubles|Manchester United won the double twice|Oldham did the double over Forest last season|he paid double and had a room all to himself|profits doubled in one year|Clare doubled her income overnight|thy fifty yet doth double five and twenty|I doubled across the deck to join the others|West's failure to double 4♥|it may be right for East to double|the muslin is doubled and then laid in a sieve over the bowl|he had one arm around her and the other fist doubled|we struck out seaward to double the headland of the cape|a laser printer doubles as a photocopier|

--Word--|dowf |--Type--|adjective, noun, verb|--Meanings--|Dull, flat; lacking in spirit or energy, listless; inactive.|Sad, melancholy, out of spirits.|Of a sound: dull, flat, hollow. Now somewhat rare.|Of a day, etc., with regard to its weather: dull, overcast; hazy. Compare duff. Now rare.|Of vegetable matter: decayed, rotten, lacking the kernel or substance. Compare deaf nut, duff. Now rare.|A dull blow, typically the result of striking with something soft; the sound made by such a blow; a thud. Also in to play dowf: to thump. Compare duff, doof [noun²]. Now rare.|To thump, buffet, punch, or strike (someone or something), especially with a soft object or substance. Also without object. Frequently with down. Occasionally also without object: to land with a thud.|--Examples--|

--Word--|Scott, Dred |--Type--|proper noun|--Meanings--|(c. 1795–1858), US slave. He brought suit for his freedom based on the fact that he had lived in free territories for five years, but the US Supreme Court ruled against him in 1857 in a case that became the focus of much heated political controversy. Scott was emancipated later that year and worked as a hotel porter in St. Louis.|--Examples--|

--Word--|dryas |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|A plant of a genus that comprises the mountain avens.|The first and third climatic stages of the late-glacial period in northern Europe, in which cold conditions prevailed and plants of the genus Dryas were abundant. a drop cloth or drop curtain.|A trapdoor on a gallows, the opening of which causes the prisoner to fall and thus be hanged.|Execution by hanging.|--Examples--|the fire was caused by someone dropping a lighted cigarette|they dropped bombs on Caen during the raid|the airlift dropped food into the camp|he dropped a goal to beat England in the final minute|he dropped a lot of acid in the Sixties|the spoon dropped with a clatter from her hand|they escaped by climbing out of the window and dropping to the ground|he dropped to his knees in the mud|he looked ready to drop|the land drops away to the river|he dropped his voice as she came into the room|pre-tax profits dropped by 37 per cent|tourism has dropped off in the last few years|the charges against him were dropped last year|they were dropped from the team in the reshuffle|I was under pressure from family and friends to drop Barbara|he dropped the load off at a dealer's|his mum dropped him outside and drove off to work|just drop it in the post when you've got time|she dropped a remark about having been included in the selection|various guest DJs drop quality tunes both old and new|the club have yet to drop a point in the Second Division|he reckoned I'd dropped forty thousand pounds|East drops the 10 on the second round|the first drops of rain splashed on the ground|there was not a drop of water in sight|he doesn't touch a drop during the week|eye drops|they left within five minutes of the drop of the curtain|the planes finally managed to make the drop|a significant drop in consumer spending|a sheer 1,500-foot drop|they only just avoided the drop last season|do you play for the drop now or finesse the 9?|I got to the depot and made the drop|the lavatory's water cistern could be used as a letter drop|a chocolate drop|simple amethyst and diamond drops|warders, standing on planks, invariably flanked the prisoners on the drop|

--Word--|front |--Type--|noun, adjective, verb|--Meanings--|The side or part of an object that presents itself to view or that is normally seen or used first; the most forward part of something.|The position directly ahead of someone or something; the most forward position or place.|The forward-facing part of a person's body, on the opposite side to their back.|The part of a garment covering a person's front.|A woman's bust or cleavage.|Any face of a building, especially that of the main entrance.|The foremost line or part of an armed force; the furthest position that an army has reached and where the enemy is or may be engaged.|The direction towards which a line of troops faces when formed.|A particular formation of troops for battle.|A particular situation or sphere of operation.|An organized political group.|The forward edge of an advancing mass of air.|An appearance or form of behaviour assumed by a person to conceal their genuine feelings.|A person or organization serving as a cover for subversive or illegal activities.|Boldness and confidence of manner.|A person's face or forehead.|Of or at the front.|(of a vowel sound) formed by raising the tongue, excluding the blade and tip, towards the hard palate.|(of a building or piece of land) have the front facing or directed towards.|Be or stand in front of.|Provide (something) with a front or facing of a particular type or material.|Lead or be the most prominent member in (an organization, group, or activity)|Present or host (a television or radio programme)|Act as a front or cover for illegal or secret activity.|Adopt a particular expression or form of behaviour to conceal one's genuine feelings.|Make an appearance; turn up.|Stand face to face with; confront.|Articulate (a vowel sound) with the tongue further forward.|Place (a sentence element) at the beginning of a sentence instead of in its usual position, typically for emphasis or as a feature of some dialects, as in horrible it was.|--Examples--|a page at the front of the book had been torn out|he sealed the envelope and wrote on the front|she quickly turned her head to face the front|she rolled over on to her front|porridge slopped from the tray on to his shirt front|get your eyes off my front, meathead|the west front of the Cathedral|his regiment was immediately sent to the front|the Spartans preserving an even and unbroken front|there was some good news on the jobs front|the National Progressive Patriotic Front|she put on a brave front|the CIA identified the company as a front for a terrorist group|he's got a bit of talent and a lot of front|the mark of fool set on his front|the front cover of the magazine|she was in the front garden|the flats which fronted Crow Road|both properties fronted on to the beach|they reached the hedge fronting the garden|a metal box fronted by an alloy panel|a glass-fronted bookcase|the group is fronted by two girl singers|she is set to front a new BBC show|he fronted for them in illegal property deals|I can't front, I never really listened to much of his music|parents get a bit worried if you don't front up now and then|Tom fronted him with unwavering eyes|the three velar consonants are normally fronted to some degree|the fronting of /au/ was completed a couple of generations ago|

--Word--|dulcimer |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|A musical instrument with a sounding board or box, typically trapezoid in shape, over which strings of graduated length are stretched, played by plucking or especially by being struck with handheld hammers. The term hammered dulcimer is sometimes used, especially in the US, to distinguish these from plucked instruments such as the Appalachian dulcimer.|--Examples--|
--Word--|dulcimer |--Type--|noun|--Meanings--|A musical instrument with a sounding board or box, typically trapezoid in shape, over which strings of graduated length are stretched, played by plucking or especially by being struck with handheld hammers. The term hammered dulcimer is sometimes used, especially in the US, to distinguish these from plucked instruments such as the Appalachian dulcimer.|--Examples--|

--Word--|dumb |--Type--|adjective, verb|--Meanings--|Temporarily unable or unwilling to speak.|Resulting in or expressed by speechlessness.|(of a person) unable to speak, most typically because of congenital deafness.|(of animals) unable to speak as a natural state and thus regarded as helpless or deserving pity.|Stupid.|(of a computer terminal) able only to transmit data to or receive data from a computer; having no independent processing capability.|Simplify or reduce the intellectual content of something so as to make it accessible to a larger number of people.|Become less intellectually challenging.|Make dumb or unheard; silence.|--Examples--|she stood dumb while he poured out a stream of abuse|they stared in dumb amazement|he was born deaf, dumb, and blind|a dumb question|the producers categorically deny that they're dumbing down the show|the need to dumb down for mass audiences|a splendour that dazed the mind and dumbed the tongue|

very close.|Not willing to spend or give much money; mean.|Drunk.|Very firmly, closely, or tensely.|--Examples--|she twisted her handkerchief into a tight knot|I prised the tight lid off with my knife|the dress was too tight for her|a tight-fitting top|she released her tight hold on the dog|presidential advisers keep a tight grip on domestic policy|a light-tight container|the drawcord pulls tight|he showed off his tight abs|the tight skin on your face may start to sag|there was a tight feeling in his gut|she gave him a tight smile|security was tight at yesterday's ceremony|a tight argument|the vocalists are strong and the band is tight|a tight parking spot|it was a tight squeeze in the tiny vestibule|the coach failed to negotiate the tight bend|David was out of work and money was tight|an ability to work to tight deadlines|he levered the bishop out from a tight knot of clerical wives|New York's tight Orthodox Jewish community|the folk were far too tight to let anyone know|he won in a tight finish|he is tight with his money|he got tight on brandy|he went downstairs, holding tight to the bannisters|
